WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.710 --> 00:00:02.880
WALEED KADOUS: OK, thank
you very much.

00:00:02.880 --> 00:00:05.000
We're really excited that
you've joined us today.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:08.140
My name is Waleed Kadous, and
next to me is Sarah Peterson,

00:00:08.140 --> 00:00:10.630
the Business Product Manager
for Indoor Maps.

00:00:10.630 --> 00:00:14.490
And we're really excited to talk
to you today about Indoor

00:00:14.490 --> 00:00:18.100
Maps and their potential to make
people's lives a little

00:00:18.100 --> 00:00:21.900
less tedious, a little less
annoying, so they can get on

00:00:21.900 --> 00:00:24.690
with what they really want to
get on about and do whatever

00:00:24.690 --> 00:00:26.720
it is that they want to do,
just as Larry mentioned in

00:00:26.720 --> 00:00:27.880
today's keynote.

00:00:27.880 --> 00:00:32.060
So here's what we want to plan
to talk about today.

00:00:32.060 --> 00:00:34.990
We want to tell you why we think
indoors are important,

00:00:34.990 --> 00:00:38.170
and now is a critical time
for Indoor Maps.

00:00:38.170 --> 00:00:41.150
We want to walk you through what
we have right now, what

00:00:41.150 --> 00:00:44.370
the state of the current product
is, where we're up to.

00:00:44.370 --> 00:00:47.330
And then we want to take you a
little bit behind the curtain

00:00:47.330 --> 00:00:50.420
of how we made Indoor
Maps, how they work.

00:00:50.420 --> 00:00:52.930
And we're going to share some
stuff with you today that we

00:00:52.930 --> 00:00:55.510
haven't shared publicly before,
and that's what we're

00:00:55.510 --> 00:00:58.720
really excited about as well,
and we look forward to your

00:00:58.720 --> 00:00:59.580
questions and answers.

00:00:59.580 --> 00:01:02.110
And finally, we want to
discuss with you, as

00:01:02.110 --> 00:01:04.480
developers, some of the exciting
opportunities we

00:01:04.480 --> 00:01:09.340
think are coming for Indoor
Location and Indoor Maps.

00:01:09.340 --> 00:01:12.960
So why do we care about
Indoor Maps so much?

00:01:12.960 --> 00:01:14.770
So here's the first reason.

00:01:14.770 --> 00:01:18.620
According to the EPA,
people spend 90%

00:01:18.620 --> 00:01:20.370
of their time indoors.

00:01:20.370 --> 00:01:22.740
And some of you might
say, well, what's

00:01:22.740 --> 00:01:23.560
the point of that?

00:01:23.560 --> 00:01:26.860
Half of that is me sleeping in
bed, and the other half is

00:01:26.860 --> 00:01:28.140
when I'm at work.

00:01:28.140 --> 00:01:30.320
But when you actually look at
where people spend, and you

00:01:30.320 --> 00:01:33.490
just focus on public
indoor spaces--

00:01:33.490 --> 00:01:37.300
places like restaurants, places
like Moscone Center

00:01:37.300 --> 00:01:38.210
right now--

00:01:38.210 --> 00:01:41.380
those types of places, they
spend about an hour, hour and

00:01:41.380 --> 00:01:43.960
a half in shopping and all
of those kinds of things.

00:01:43.960 --> 00:01:47.100
Now just as Larry mentioned
today, by comparison, people

00:01:47.100 --> 00:01:51.760
spend about 50 minutes every day
outdoors or commuting and

00:01:51.760 --> 00:01:53.720
just getting from
place to place.

00:01:53.720 --> 00:01:57.060
Yet we've devoted a huge amount
of our efforts to this

00:01:57.060 --> 00:02:01.290
application that works in the
outdoor case, but we haven't

00:02:01.290 --> 00:02:04.160
really spent a lot of time
on the indoor case.

00:02:04.160 --> 00:02:07.240
And I want to tell you a little
bit more just to give

00:02:07.240 --> 00:02:13.880
you an idea of how present
Indoors can be.

00:02:13.880 --> 00:02:17.110
So I want you to think about
what it's like for people in

00:02:17.110 --> 00:02:21.550
Tokyo, and here's, actually, a
story that happened to me.

00:02:21.550 --> 00:02:24.750
I went to visit Google's office
in Roppongi Hills,

00:02:24.750 --> 00:02:26.560
which is a beautiful,
beautiful office.

00:02:26.560 --> 00:02:29.590
I checked into the hotel,
the Grand Hyatt.

00:02:29.590 --> 00:02:32.600
I went downstairs, had breakfast
in their cafe.

00:02:32.600 --> 00:02:35.600
I went to Google's office, and
if you guys ever get the

00:02:35.600 --> 00:02:38.310
opportunity to visit the Google
office there in Tokyo,

00:02:38.310 --> 00:02:41.090
it's an amazing, amazing
office with

00:02:41.090 --> 00:02:42.830
views of Mount Fuji.

00:02:42.830 --> 00:02:45.840
And then some of my other
colleagues at Google decided

00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:49.220
it was time for us to go out and
get some food for dinner.

00:02:49.220 --> 00:02:51.670
And sure enough, we hopped
on the train.

00:02:51.670 --> 00:02:54.480
We changed trains twice, and
then we ended up at this

00:02:54.480 --> 00:02:57.260
beautiful, beautiful sushi
restaurant where we had some

00:02:57.260 --> 00:02:58.630
pretty nice food.

00:02:58.630 --> 00:03:03.200
And the amazing thing to me
about that entire trip is I

00:03:03.200 --> 00:03:05.620
wasn't outdoors once.

00:03:05.620 --> 00:03:07.920
I was indoors the entire time.

00:03:07.920 --> 00:03:10.270
And that's what it's like to
live in a place like Tokyo or

00:03:10.270 --> 00:03:12.990
Singapore or one of those
other urbanized centers.

00:03:12.990 --> 00:03:15.980
And if you can't provide
information to people in that

00:03:15.980 --> 00:03:20.390
kind of environment about how
to go about their daily

00:03:20.390 --> 00:03:22.310
business, then you're
not really

00:03:22.310 --> 00:03:24.740
delivering a great service.

00:03:24.740 --> 00:03:28.890
So I want to focus on a few
particular classes and ways

00:03:28.890 --> 00:03:32.620
that we can use Indoor Maps to
make people's experiences

00:03:32.620 --> 00:03:35.140
easier and to get the
inconvenient questions out of

00:03:35.140 --> 00:03:36.040
their lives.

00:03:36.040 --> 00:03:39.370
The first is that we can enhance
existing products.

00:03:39.370 --> 00:03:42.420
You can imagine if we can answer
questions like, is

00:03:42.420 --> 00:03:45.510
there an ATM inside here, or I
need to find the restrooms

00:03:45.510 --> 00:03:49.420
quickly, those types of things,
we can really remove a

00:03:49.420 --> 00:03:53.950
lot of the annoyance
in people's lives.

00:03:53.950 --> 00:03:56.770
But there's another class of
applications that's not

00:03:56.770 --> 00:03:59.960
foreground applications like
this, where the user comes to

00:03:59.960 --> 00:04:01.680
you and asks a question.

00:04:01.680 --> 00:04:03.790
Those are background
applications, what we would

00:04:03.790 --> 00:04:06.840
call contextual apps, and we
really think there's a lot of

00:04:06.840 --> 00:04:10.650
potential there for Indoor Maps
and Location to enhance

00:04:10.650 --> 00:04:12.560
the performance on that
particular front.

00:04:12.560 --> 00:04:14.650
And I'm going to come back to
that at the end of the session

00:04:14.650 --> 00:04:17.480
just to kind of point you as we
look forward to what we can

00:04:17.480 --> 00:04:18.730
do with that.

00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:21.350
All right.

00:04:21.350 --> 00:04:24.010
So let's take a deep dive.

00:04:24.010 --> 00:04:28.160
Let's say you buy my story and
you agree that Indoor Maps are

00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:29.800
really very useful.

00:04:29.800 --> 00:04:32.290
Let's just do a deep dive, find
out what the different

00:04:32.290 --> 00:04:33.090
components are.

00:04:33.090 --> 00:04:36.570
So on the left here, you can see
what it looks like before

00:04:36.570 --> 00:04:39.370
we add Indoor Maps to a venue,
and on the right here, you can

00:04:39.370 --> 00:04:40.850
see what we end up
with afterwards.

00:04:40.850 --> 00:04:43.530
You can see we've added
a lot more detail.

00:04:43.530 --> 00:04:45.550
There's the Floor Selector
over here.

00:04:45.550 --> 00:04:47.850
You've noticed that the blue
dot and the blue circle are

00:04:47.850 --> 00:04:48.700
strengthened.

00:04:48.700 --> 00:04:50.070
So you can see that there's
a lot of work

00:04:50.070 --> 00:04:50.980
that goes into this.

00:04:50.980 --> 00:04:53.960
This happens to be the Mall of
America, which is the biggest

00:04:53.960 --> 00:04:55.390
mall in the United States.

00:04:55.390 --> 00:04:57.790
It's so big there's a theme
park in the middle, and in

00:04:57.790 --> 00:05:01.110
wintertime, runners run around
the loop because it's too cold

00:05:01.110 --> 00:05:02.450
to go running outside.

00:05:02.450 --> 00:05:05.280
And if you were in that type of
venue, can you imagine if

00:05:05.280 --> 00:05:08.140
you didn't have Indoor Maps if
you wanted to find someone?

00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:12.380
Four levels of just retail after
retail after retail.

00:05:12.380 --> 00:05:15.480
You can see how valuable having
indoor information is.

00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:17.720
Let's zoom in for a moment
just to kind of see.

00:05:17.720 --> 00:05:20.690
So as well as the big picture,
you have the other

00:05:20.690 --> 00:05:22.220
information.

00:05:22.220 --> 00:05:23.750
Over here, you have
the restrooms.

00:05:23.750 --> 00:05:25.510
You have information desk.

00:05:25.510 --> 00:05:27.540
You have elevators
and escalators.

00:05:27.540 --> 00:05:28.990
All of that's got to be added.

00:05:28.990 --> 00:05:31.570
And what's interesting is those,
what we call points of

00:05:31.570 --> 00:05:34.970
interest, vary from
place to place.

00:05:34.970 --> 00:05:37.630
If you're at an airport, what
you care about is the airport

00:05:37.630 --> 00:05:38.870
baggage carousels.

00:05:38.870 --> 00:05:41.490
If you're in a museum, you care
about the displays and

00:05:41.490 --> 00:05:42.720
the exhibitions.

00:05:42.720 --> 00:05:45.420
And if you're in a department
store, you care about men's

00:05:45.420 --> 00:05:48.700
shoes or whatever else it is
that you're looking for.

00:05:48.700 --> 00:05:51.060
And as well as that, you need
to know the walking paths so

00:05:51.060 --> 00:05:54.010
we can give you really
high-quality

00:05:54.010 --> 00:05:55.920
directions as well.

00:05:55.920 --> 00:05:58.590
But there's another component
as well as the map, which we

00:05:58.590 --> 00:06:02.780
call a location, of course, and
here's the tricky part.

00:06:02.780 --> 00:06:05.960
Maps don't really become that
useful if you don't know where

00:06:05.960 --> 00:06:08.210
you are relative to them.

00:06:08.210 --> 00:06:11.690
And we really care a lot about
user location and getting the

00:06:11.690 --> 00:06:13.740
user's location as accurate
as possible.

00:06:13.740 --> 00:06:16.330
So this is a screenshot from
the Bloomingdale's that's

00:06:16.330 --> 00:06:19.170
around the corner or across the
road from here, where we

00:06:19.170 --> 00:06:23.090
have Indoor Maps and Indoor
location, and I just wanted to

00:06:23.090 --> 00:06:26.176
give you a feel of the different
error metrics.

00:06:26.176 --> 00:06:30.350
So this circle shows about
25-meter accuracy.

00:06:30.350 --> 00:06:33.790
So 25 meters, 30 meters, roughly
speaking, that's what

00:06:33.790 --> 00:06:36.870
you get from a network-based
location.

00:06:36.870 --> 00:06:41.000
So you can see it's not really
very useful to the user.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:43.820
He could be in one of four
different departments.

00:06:43.820 --> 00:06:46.670
He could be in women's
fragrances or cosmetics.

00:06:46.670 --> 00:06:48.680
We just don't have a clue.

00:06:48.680 --> 00:06:51.215
So if you just showed this
circle to the user, it

00:06:51.215 --> 00:06:52.900
wouldn't be very useful.

00:06:52.900 --> 00:06:54.550
Now here's the interesting
thing.

00:06:54.550 --> 00:06:59.660
Let's go to 15 meters, and
that's a little bit better.

00:06:59.660 --> 00:07:01.970
We're starting to work out maybe
they're only in one of

00:07:01.970 --> 00:07:03.560
three different departments.

00:07:03.560 --> 00:07:05.540
Now, here's something I
want you to notice.

00:07:05.540 --> 00:07:09.080
15 meters is about what
you get with GPS.

00:07:09.080 --> 00:07:12.150
So what I want you to realize
is that the error levels for

00:07:12.150 --> 00:07:13.840
Location and Indoors
are even higher.

00:07:13.840 --> 00:07:18.210
And it's only when you get to
5-ish, 10-ish meters that you

00:07:18.210 --> 00:07:18.950
start to get useful.

00:07:18.950 --> 00:07:21.520
You can identify right
away where you are.

00:07:21.520 --> 00:07:25.090
And at the 6-meter level, it
varies a lot from place to

00:07:25.090 --> 00:07:27.130
place what accuracy
levels we get.

00:07:27.130 --> 00:07:31.240
But roughly speaking, 6 meters
is kind of the mean of the

00:07:31.240 --> 00:07:34.130
performance when we do
high-quality location.

00:07:34.130 --> 00:07:36.900
And of course, our goal is to
get to 1 meter, at which point

00:07:36.900 --> 00:07:39.320
you can really, really
accurately place yourself and

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:41.450
you can help the user find
what they need to find.

00:07:44.390 --> 00:07:47.650
So I really want to tell you why
I'm excited to be talking

00:07:47.650 --> 00:07:49.170
to you today.

00:07:49.170 --> 00:07:51.590
It's really about these four
things that are coming

00:07:51.590 --> 00:07:53.980
together right at this
very moment.

00:07:53.980 --> 00:07:55.560
Google now has some
really, really

00:07:55.560 --> 00:07:56.960
good indoor maps coverage.

00:07:56.960 --> 00:08:01.590
In fact, imagine we took all
of our indoor maps, all of

00:08:01.590 --> 00:08:05.010
them, and tiled them end to
end, you'd have enough to

00:08:05.010 --> 00:08:07.640
cover the entire city
of San Francisco.

00:08:07.640 --> 00:08:10.010
And in fact, not just that, but
you'd need a pretty decent

00:08:10.010 --> 00:08:16.090
mezzanine, almost an entire
other floor to really show

00:08:16.090 --> 00:08:18.040
what the extent of our coverage
is, and we're going

00:08:18.040 --> 00:08:22.350
to keep adding San
Francisco-sized floors as we

00:08:22.350 --> 00:08:24.880
move forward.

00:08:24.880 --> 00:08:27.520
Not only that, but there's the
possibility of adding the

00:08:27.520 --> 00:08:30.280
high-quality indoor location,
as I mentioned.

00:08:30.280 --> 00:08:33.960
Combine that with self-service
tools that allow people like

00:08:33.960 --> 00:08:38.730
business owners and venue owners
to upload Location and

00:08:38.730 --> 00:08:43.190
Indoor Maps, as well as
improving developer APIs, and

00:08:43.190 --> 00:08:45.830
I have to ask the question,
are we getting close to a

00:08:45.830 --> 00:08:47.880
tipping point on Indoor Maps?

00:08:47.880 --> 00:08:51.850
And let me be clear what I
mean by a tipping point.

00:08:51.850 --> 00:08:56.910
So maybe some of you are old
enough to remember 1999, that

00:08:56.910 --> 00:09:00.950
between 1999 and 2003, there
was this really weird

00:09:00.950 --> 00:09:02.970
transition that happened
to the web.

00:09:02.970 --> 00:09:05.900
If you found a company or a
business, and you searched for

00:09:05.900 --> 00:09:08.920
them on the web, and you found
they had a web page, you'd be

00:09:08.920 --> 00:09:09.630
like, cool.

00:09:09.630 --> 00:09:12.380
That company is kind of
ahead of the curve.

00:09:12.380 --> 00:09:17.480
And then by 2003, what happened
was you found a

00:09:17.480 --> 00:09:19.460
business or company, you looked
for their website, and

00:09:19.460 --> 00:09:21.870
if they didn't have one,
you'd be like,

00:09:21.870 --> 00:09:22.630
what's wrong with them?

00:09:22.630 --> 00:09:25.270
Why aren't they keeping
up with the times?

00:09:25.270 --> 00:09:28.650
And in fact, it's borne
out by the statistics.

00:09:28.650 --> 00:09:32.560
I took the statistics for the
growth of domain name

00:09:32.560 --> 00:09:35.960
registrations between
1999 and 2003.

00:09:35.960 --> 00:09:40.070
And whap, in the space of
four years, domain name

00:09:40.070 --> 00:09:44.390
registrations grew by a factor
of 33, which is incredible.

00:09:44.390 --> 00:09:47.410
And what I'm wondering is, is
Indoors on the verge of the

00:09:47.410 --> 00:09:47.880
same thing?

00:09:47.880 --> 00:09:50.100
We have all of the
prerequisites.

00:09:50.100 --> 00:09:54.760
Will we go to a place where
you open Google Maps on

00:09:54.760 --> 00:09:56.700
Android right now, and you see
floor plans for Moscone and

00:09:56.700 --> 00:09:58.750
you go, ooh, that's
kind of cool.

00:09:58.750 --> 00:10:01.440
But going to a business
somewhere, and then all of a

00:10:01.440 --> 00:10:03.670
sudden, you pull out your phone,
and they don't have a

00:10:03.670 --> 00:10:05.660
map and you'll be like, what's
wrong with this business?

00:10:05.660 --> 00:10:07.620
Why don't they have
Indoor Maps?

00:10:07.620 --> 00:10:10.400
And I think we may be on the
cusp of that very, very

00:10:10.400 --> 00:10:13.230
exciting transition.

00:10:13.230 --> 00:10:16.120
So you guys are like, well yeah,
I mean, he's preaching

00:10:16.120 --> 00:10:16.840
to the converted.

00:10:16.840 --> 00:10:18.280
Why don't we have
this already?

00:10:18.280 --> 00:10:21.160
I wanted to spend a few minutes
to explain to you the

00:10:21.160 --> 00:10:24.450
challenges that we face as we
try to really move the needle

00:10:24.450 --> 00:10:26.550
on Indoor Maps.

00:10:26.550 --> 00:10:30.210
So the first problem you have is
where do you get your floor

00:10:30.210 --> 00:10:31.440
plans from?

00:10:31.440 --> 00:10:35.470
When you're outdoors, let's say
that you wanted to do maps

00:10:35.470 --> 00:10:36.850
for the entire US.

00:10:36.850 --> 00:10:39.090
You can actually go to the US
Census, and there's this

00:10:39.090 --> 00:10:42.830
really nice data set called
Tiger, and it has road names,

00:10:42.830 --> 00:10:45.370
and address ranges, and the
geography, and the layout, and

00:10:45.370 --> 00:10:48.860
the suburbs, and the cities, a
huge amount of information.

00:10:48.860 --> 00:10:52.430
But that information doesn't
exist indoors in the same way.

00:10:52.430 --> 00:10:53.840
And as well as that, we
don't even have the

00:10:53.840 --> 00:10:54.940
means to verify it.

00:10:54.940 --> 00:10:58.350
So as we'll talk about-- and
there'll be a presentation

00:10:58.350 --> 00:10:59.820
after this about
Ground Truth--

00:10:59.820 --> 00:11:02.450
we use Street View and aerial
imagery to really get the

00:11:02.450 --> 00:11:06.110
quality of our outdoor maps up,
so it's going to be hard

00:11:06.110 --> 00:11:07.720
to do that.

00:11:07.720 --> 00:11:11.970
The second thing is that
location is very challenging.

00:11:11.970 --> 00:11:14.390
As we mentioned, the first
problem is that you've got a

00:11:14.390 --> 00:11:15.290
higher bar to meet.

00:11:15.290 --> 00:11:19.000
Just bringing GPS indoors, even
if you could do it, would

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:21.250
not be good enough, and
that's the problem.

00:11:21.250 --> 00:11:24.910
GPS doesn't work indoors, and
I think users don't realize

00:11:24.910 --> 00:11:26.280
that this is the case.

00:11:26.280 --> 00:11:28.860
But if you were to pull out a
phone right now, you'd get the

00:11:28.860 --> 00:11:32.550
blinking GPS sign, and you'd
probably get it all day

00:11:32.550 --> 00:11:35.160
because the satellites just
can't get in here.

00:11:35.160 --> 00:11:38.860
So you can't use GPS, and one of
the worst things about GPS

00:11:38.860 --> 00:11:42.000
is you can't estimate elevation
very accurately.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:43.980
So we're going to have to
come up with some other

00:11:43.980 --> 00:11:47.340
technologies that help
us to determine which

00:11:47.340 --> 00:11:48.860
level someone is on.

00:11:48.860 --> 00:11:51.360
And some of you who know your
sensors on the phones are

00:11:51.360 --> 00:11:54.030
saying, well, we could use
the barometer, right?

00:11:54.030 --> 00:11:55.710
That's a really, really
accurate sensor.

00:11:55.710 --> 00:11:59.930
In fact, if you have a phone
and you open the barometer,

00:11:59.930 --> 00:12:02.610
