00:23:47.930 --> 00:23:49.990
after this in Room Nine.

00:23:49.990 --> 00:23:52.345
And they will show you more
about how these tools work and

00:23:52.345 --> 00:23:58.346
exactly how we build out our
maps in Google Earth.

00:23:58.346 --> 00:24:00.460
WALEED KADOUS: Thank you
very much, Sarah.

00:24:00.460 --> 00:24:03.540
So there are always two
parts to this, right?

00:24:03.540 --> 00:24:05.010
There's the maps and there's
the location.

00:24:05.010 --> 00:24:07.110
So let's dive into the
location side.

00:24:07.110 --> 00:24:10.580
So before I mentioned, and in
these coming slides, I'm going

00:24:10.580 --> 00:24:12.750
to refer to what I call
high-quality indoor location

00:24:12.750 --> 00:24:14.120
versus normal quality.

00:24:14.120 --> 00:24:17.050
Maybe the best way to start is
with a demonstration of that.

00:24:17.050 --> 00:24:21.210
So what I'm going to show you
now is, again, I didn't think

00:24:21.210 --> 00:24:22.580
this level particularly.

00:24:22.580 --> 00:24:23.900
This is just the Bloomingdale's

00:24:23.900 --> 00:24:25.700
immediately behind us.

00:24:25.700 --> 00:24:28.410
So let me just zoom out,
and what we have

00:24:28.410 --> 00:24:31.180
here is normal quality.

00:24:31.180 --> 00:24:34.510
The yellow dot here, that's our
estimate based on normal

00:24:34.510 --> 00:24:37.975
quality, and the green dot
is Ground Truth's.

00:24:37.975 --> 00:24:40.780
So Google sent someone out to
actually tell us where they

00:24:40.780 --> 00:24:43.310
were walking, and this is
our estimate if we use

00:24:43.310 --> 00:24:45.710
normal-quality location
indoors.

00:24:45.710 --> 00:24:47.050
And let's actually
see how it works.

00:24:47.050 --> 00:24:49.620
So it kind of follows at
the beginning, but it

00:24:49.620 --> 00:24:51.320
jumps around a lot.

00:24:51.320 --> 00:24:53.800
And then as the user comes down
to the second half of the

00:24:53.800 --> 00:24:56.940
building, it doesn't
really follow them.

00:24:56.940 --> 00:24:59.520
But if you actually do the math
on this, this is about

00:24:59.520 --> 00:25:02.080
25-meter level accuracy.

00:25:02.080 --> 00:25:04.550
You can see it's not doing a
very good job of following the

00:25:04.550 --> 00:25:07.980
user in the sense that if
someone is looking at a map,

00:25:07.980 --> 00:25:10.010
the user is there, he pulls out
his phone, and he's like,

00:25:10.010 --> 00:25:11.680
where am on this map?

00:25:11.680 --> 00:25:12.860
It's not very useful.

00:25:12.860 --> 00:25:15.280
It just seems to linger
near the entrance.

00:25:15.280 --> 00:25:17.640
Now let's actually look what
happens after we've applied

00:25:17.640 --> 00:25:19.015
high-quality indoor location.

00:25:24.210 --> 00:25:29.720
Again, just to emphasize here,
yellow is our estimate based

00:25:29.720 --> 00:25:32.210
on high-quality indoor
location, and

00:25:32.210 --> 00:25:33.900
green is Ground Truth.

00:25:33.900 --> 00:25:37.590
And you'll see here now that it
still has its flaws, it's

00:25:37.590 --> 00:25:38.630
not perfect.

00:25:38.630 --> 00:25:41.350
It seems to be out by about
6 or 7 meters here.

00:25:41.350 --> 00:25:43.850
But very quickly, you'll see it
does a pretty good job of

00:25:43.850 --> 00:25:45.440
following the user around.

00:25:45.440 --> 00:25:48.390
And so if you were the user,
this would be much, much, much

00:25:48.390 --> 00:25:48.910
more useful.

00:25:48.910 --> 00:25:50.580
If you were looking for fitting
rooms or something

00:25:50.580 --> 00:25:53.550
like that, you could use
this a lot more easily.

00:25:53.550 --> 00:25:57.480
So the question then is, how
is it that we actually get

00:25:57.480 --> 00:26:00.010
these high-quality indoor
location models?

00:26:05.160 --> 00:26:08.940
And just to highlight this,
I think in the keynote you

00:26:08.940 --> 00:26:10.460
remember Hugo Barra
talked about the

00:26:10.460 --> 00:26:11.860
Fused Location Provider.

00:26:11.860 --> 00:26:14.330
These results are using that
Fused Location Provider that

00:26:14.330 --> 00:26:17.000
mixes us all of the sensors
on the phone together.

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:20.070
So what we actually have is we
have a tool called Google Maps

00:26:20.070 --> 00:26:21.630
Floor Plan Markup.

00:26:21.630 --> 00:26:22.380
That's an app.

00:26:22.380 --> 00:26:24.255
You can just search for it on
the web, grab it, and download

00:26:24.255 --> 00:26:25.680
it, and install it.

00:26:25.680 --> 00:26:28.740
And let's say that you had
uploaded a floor plan, as

00:26:28.740 --> 00:26:31.740
Sarah had outlined in the
previous stage, and it had

00:26:31.740 --> 00:26:32.880
been approved.

00:26:32.880 --> 00:26:35.670
Then as a second, optional
step, you can do the

00:26:35.670 --> 00:26:36.790
normal-quality location.

00:26:36.790 --> 00:26:38.390
It will still kind of work.

00:26:38.390 --> 00:26:40.730
But it won't give you a levels,
and it won't give you

00:26:40.730 --> 00:26:42.946
that high accuracy.

00:26:42.946 --> 00:26:46.390
So what we do is you can then,
as an optional second step,

00:26:46.390 --> 00:26:48.970
help the process by gathering
location.

00:26:48.970 --> 00:26:51.780
So this shows the floor plan
that you uploaded in this

00:26:51.780 --> 00:26:55.180
particular case, yet another
one of Google's buildings.

00:26:55.180 --> 00:26:59.300
And then what happens is you
move this circle around until

00:26:59.300 --> 00:27:00.630
it shows where you are.

00:27:00.630 --> 00:27:04.240
You hit this marker over here
down on the bottom, and then

00:27:04.240 --> 00:27:05.830
that drops a point.

00:27:05.830 --> 00:27:08.760
And then what we ask you to do
is to walk through the level,

00:27:08.760 --> 00:27:12.610
basically marking where you've
been, and traverse the entire

00:27:12.610 --> 00:27:15.340
level, leaving a snail
trail behind.

00:27:15.340 --> 00:27:19.940
And we use that information to
then build that high-quality

00:27:19.940 --> 00:27:21.930
indoor location model.

00:27:21.930 --> 00:27:24.532
Now, a few things I want to
highlight about this.

00:27:24.532 --> 00:27:26.240
This is the self-service
model.

00:27:26.240 --> 00:27:30.660
For more complicated and not
quite as detailed and even

00:27:30.660 --> 00:27:34.200
more detailed venues, actually,
Google has its own

00:27:34.200 --> 00:27:36.060
team that it sends out
with a professional

00:27:36.060 --> 00:27:37.790
version of this tool.

00:27:37.790 --> 00:27:39.580
But one thing I also wanted
to highlight is the

00:27:39.580 --> 00:27:40.410
data that we collect.

00:27:40.410 --> 00:27:45.390
So we collect a variety of
sensors, but we do collect

00:27:45.390 --> 00:27:50.250
Wi-Fi, especially the BSSID
and the RSSI, but we don't

00:27:50.250 --> 00:27:52.510
collect SSIDs and we
don't collect data.

00:27:52.510 --> 00:27:54.870
And if you're interested in
actually reading the source

00:27:54.870 --> 00:27:56.740
code that's at the heart of
the collection of this

00:27:56.740 --> 00:27:58.500
algorithm, that's available.

00:27:58.500 --> 00:28:01.810
If you look on code.google.com
under Sensor Data Collection

00:28:01.810 --> 00:28:04.180
Library, you should be
able to find it.

00:28:04.180 --> 00:28:07.640
So what happens is that you
basically go through your

00:28:07.640 --> 00:28:12.340
venue, labeling where you are
against landmarks in the floor

00:28:12.340 --> 00:28:15.240
plan, and then you
do this twice.

00:28:15.240 --> 00:28:20.800
And you upload these data
collections, the marker walks,

00:28:20.800 --> 00:28:23.870
up to Google servers, and then
we basically chew on them for

00:28:23.870 --> 00:28:26.760
a little while, and we process
them so that we can deliver

00:28:26.760 --> 00:28:29.570
this high-quality model.

00:28:29.570 --> 00:28:31.700
Now, let's talk a little bit
about what we do next to

00:28:31.700 --> 00:28:34.370
determine where the user is.

00:28:34.370 --> 00:28:36.390
So really what happens-- and I'm
going to walk you through

00:28:36.390 --> 00:28:37.410
the process.

00:28:37.410 --> 00:28:40.580
We actually combine a lot of
different sensors to give you

00:28:40.580 --> 00:28:41.510
that one estimate.

00:28:41.510 --> 00:28:42.830
We use the Wi-Fi.

00:28:42.830 --> 00:28:44.340
We use GPS.

00:28:44.340 --> 00:28:47.050
We use the sensors, so that's
the accelerometer, the

00:28:47.050 --> 00:28:51.920
gyroscope on your phone, the
barometer as well potentially.

00:28:51.920 --> 00:28:54.370
But the truth of the matter,
when you come down to it, is

00:28:54.370 --> 00:28:58.810
the one that we actually
dominate in a lot of these

00:28:58.810 --> 00:29:01.440
calculations for absolute
position where you are within

00:29:01.440 --> 00:29:03.940
the level is Wi-Fi.

00:29:03.940 --> 00:29:05.740
And Wi-Fi has a lot
of problems when

00:29:05.740 --> 00:29:07.330
you use it for location.

00:29:07.330 --> 00:29:11.540
It really wasn't designed with
location in mind in any way.

00:29:11.540 --> 00:29:14.970
And it's very, very sensitive,
especially it's very sensitive

00:29:14.970 --> 00:29:19.070
to bags of water that happen to
be moving around, getting

00:29:19.070 --> 00:29:22.740
in the way between the
APs and the signal.

00:29:22.740 --> 00:29:26.300
And it just so happens that
humans are, more or less, bags

00:29:26.300 --> 00:29:29.220
of water, at least as far
as Wi-Fi is concerned.

00:29:29.220 --> 00:29:32.540
So you can imagine that at
really crowded venues like

00:29:32.540 --> 00:29:34.500
this one where Wi-Fi is already
a challenge and you

00:29:34.500 --> 00:29:36.540
have lots of bodies, Wi-Fi
isn't going to

00:29:36.540 --> 00:29:37.840
behave in the same way.

00:29:37.840 --> 00:29:40.690
And sometimes it can be
something really trivial, like

00:29:40.690 --> 00:29:43.170
imagine that there's
big metal shutters.

00:29:43.170 --> 00:29:47.200
They have a huge impact on the
way that Wi-Fi is perceived.

00:29:47.200 --> 00:29:50.100
And the real issue is there's
this thing called RSSI, which

00:29:50.100 --> 00:29:52.790
is the signal strength, and that
doesn't really give you a

00:29:52.790 --> 00:29:56.660
good estimate of how far away
you are from the AP.

00:29:56.660 --> 00:30:01.100
And then the other problem is
every phone measures Wi-Fi in

00:30:01.100 --> 00:30:02.470
a slightly different way.

00:30:02.470 --> 00:30:05.300
So you must be thinking, there
must be some other really good

00:30:05.300 --> 00:30:11.790
reasons why Google chose to use
Wi-Fi for indoor location.

00:30:11.790 --> 00:30:12.680
Not really.

00:30:12.680 --> 00:30:15.820
There's only really one, and
that is that it's available

00:30:15.820 --> 00:30:18.490
absolutely or pretty
much everywhere.

00:30:18.490 --> 00:30:21.740
So many indoor venues have Wi-Fi
coverage that we can

00:30:21.740 --> 00:30:25.390
actually do this indoor stuff,
and that's really its only

00:30:25.390 --> 00:30:29.000
redeeming feature, to
be honest with you.

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:31.590
And so we thought that Indoor
is still compelling enough

00:30:31.590 --> 00:30:33.830
that even though there are all
of these technical challenges

00:30:33.830 --> 00:30:36.470
that we have to overcome and
it's not perfect, we still

00:30:36.470 --> 00:30:40.530
think there's a lot of value,
and we can outperform GPS in

00:30:40.530 --> 00:30:41.980
many situations.

00:30:41.980 --> 00:30:43.400
So I want to walk you through.

00:30:43.400 --> 00:30:47.820
Now that we've built these Wi-Fi
models, what does the

00:30:47.820 --> 00:30:51.820
interaction between your phone
and Google servers look like?

00:30:51.820 --> 00:30:54.150
And I want to emphasize that
this is, of course, anonymous.

00:30:54.150 --> 00:30:56.460
It's not user specific
in any way.

00:30:56.460 --> 00:30:59.610
And basically, what happens is
the first thing we check is,

00:30:59.610 --> 00:31:02.800
do we have a high-quality
location model at this

00:31:02.800 --> 00:31:04.340
particular venue?

00:31:04.340 --> 00:31:07.270
If we do, we then determine if
you're indoors or outdoors.

00:31:07.270 --> 00:31:10.020
And if we determine that you're
indoors, then we send

00:31:10.020 --> 00:31:11.310
what's called a Level
Selector.

00:31:11.310 --> 00:31:12.100
And the Level Selector--

00:31:12.100 --> 00:31:13.455
say, we're here at Moscone..

00:31:13.455 --> 00:31:15.800
There would be three levels
that you could be on, one,

00:31:15.800 --> 00:31:18.490
two, or three, and it
would report, two.

00:31:18.490 --> 00:31:20.880
And I think actually, Sarah
might have something she wants

00:31:20.880 --> 00:31:22.130
to show us.

00:31:25.130 --> 00:31:27.861
So let me just zoom that in.

00:31:27.861 --> 00:31:31.280
SARAH PETERSON: So we spent a
little bit of quality time at

00:31:31.280 --> 00:31:34.306
Moscone yesterday to
try and build out

00:31:34.306 --> 00:31:35.240
some new indoor models.

00:31:35.240 --> 00:31:38.720
And what you will see here,
this is where we are right

00:31:38.720 --> 00:31:42.275
now, and it's actually pretty
accurate, I'd say.

00:31:42.275 --> 00:31:44.795
I don't know if you guys can see
that, but we're actually

00:31:44.795 --> 00:31:51.606
in a combination of rooms, 2010
and 2012, and it has them

00:31:51.606 --> 00:31:52.078
right there.

00:31:52.078 --> 00:31:55.990
So we're actually a little bit
flaky maybe, but this is what

00:31:55.990 --> 00:31:56.540
we provide.

00:31:56.540 --> 00:31:59.920
And if you're using this
throughout Moscone, we will

00:31:59.920 --> 00:32:01.540
note it is a little bit flaky.

00:32:01.540 --> 00:32:03.220
You may have noticed also that
the wireless here is

00:32:03.220 --> 00:32:04.660
a little bit flaky.

00:32:04.660 --> 00:32:08.006
They are moving, actually, all
around, and so you're not

00:32:08.006 --> 00:32:09.900
going to get the ideal
indoor experience.

00:32:09.900 --> 00:32:13.072
But definitely this is what
we're looking to provide, and

00:32:13.072 --> 00:32:15.790
it works really, really well.

00:32:15.790 --> 00:32:17.080
WALEED KADOUS: You'll also
notice that there was a blue

00:32:17.080 --> 00:32:19.540
dot there that showed
the level.

00:32:19.540 --> 00:32:23.510
So what will happen is when
you are at a venue and say

00:32:23.510 --> 00:32:25.910
you're on the escalator, as you
go between floors, it will

00:32:25.910 --> 00:32:28.620
automatically flip so that it's
always showing you what

00:32:28.620 --> 00:32:30.080
current level that you're on.

00:32:30.080 --> 00:32:33.160
So what you're seeing there,
that blue dot on the 2, that's

00:32:33.160 --> 00:32:35.210
the output of the
Level Selector.

00:32:35.210 --> 00:32:36.840
That's the thing that tells
you, am I on floor

00:32:36.840 --> 00:32:38.950
one, two, or three?

00:32:38.950 --> 00:32:44.040
So we send this little Level
Selector down to the phone,

00:32:44.040 --> 00:32:46.730
and once the Level Selector on
the phone determines what

00:32:46.730 --> 00:32:49.400
level you're on, we have this
other little component, this

00:32:49.400 --> 00:32:53.220
level model, that captures the
Wi-Fi patterns that we saw

00:32:53.220 --> 00:32:57.080
when we conducted that walk
through the building.

00:32:57.080 --> 00:32:59.610
So now let's talk about the
other side of that, which is

00:32:59.610 --> 00:33:01.120
what happens on the phone.

00:33:01.120 --> 00:33:03.710
So as I mentioned before, we
do a lot of what we call

00:33:03.710 --> 00:33:04.520
sensor fusion.

00:33:04.520 --> 00:33:07.160
If GPS is available,
we'll mix it in.

00:33:07.160 --> 00:33:09.780
But even when you do get GPS
indoor, it's subject to

00:33:09.780 --> 00:33:13.770
something called multipath
reflections because the GPS

00:33:13.770 --> 00:33:15.190
signal bounces around a lot.

00:33:15.190 --> 00:33:17.900
So we have this stage called
sensor fusion that mixes the

00:33:17.900 --> 00:33:20.970
accelerometer, the GPS, and
the Wi-Fi scan together.

00:33:20.970 --> 00:33:24.020
So now that you have the Level
Selector on your phone and the

00:33:24.020 --> 00:33:28.000
level model on your phone, you
do a Wi-Fi scan, and we run

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:30.390
the Wi-Fi scan through the Level
Selector and that tells

00:33:30.390 --> 00:33:33.400
you which level that
you're on.

00:33:33.400 --> 00:33:35.430
Once we've determined the level,
we then run the level

00:33:35.430 --> 00:33:37.910
model for this level, so we
would have one level model for

00:33:37.910 --> 00:33:40.800
each of the three different
floors of Moscone.

00:33:40.800 --> 00:33:43.180
And that feeds into it
as an input to the

00:33:43.180 --> 00:33:44.720
Sensor Fusion algorithm.

00:33:44.720 --> 00:33:47.720
And that's what computes your
long and that's what appears

00:33:47.720 --> 00:33:50.510
in Google Maps and soon through
the Fused Location

00:33:50.510 --> 00:33:52.550
Provider that we mentioned
earlier.

00:33:52.550 --> 00:33:56.310
So as you can see from here,
most of the computation's done

00:33:56.310 --> 00:33:59.350
on the phone for that extra bit
of nimbleness and speed

00:33:59.350 --> 00:34:02.510
instead of having a round
trip to the server.

00:34:02.510 --> 00:34:06.500
And with that, I'd like to talk
a little bit about what

00:34:06.500 --> 00:34:09.460
really excites us about the
future of Indoor Maps.

00:34:09.460 --> 00:34:14.520
So right now, you can actually
experiment with Indoor Maps on

00:34:14.520 --> 00:34:16.560
Google Maps Android API v2.

00:34:16.560 --> 00:34:19.540
It shows the levels, it has the
Level Selector here, it

00:34:19.540 --> 00:34:22.489
does the automatic floor
switching, and you can even

00:34:22.489 --> 00:34:25.969
control the camera to get it to
look at the right things,

00:34:25.969 --> 00:34:27.479
whatever it is that you're
interested in.

00:34:27.479 --> 00:34:31.330
In addition, we're making
available, as part of the

00:34:31.330 --> 00:34:33.219
announcement that Fused Location
Provider, there's a

00:34:33.219 --> 00:34:35.870
component that's going to be in
Google Play services called

00:34:35.870 --> 00:34:38.320
the Location Client, and that
will provide you the

00:34:38.320 --> 00:34:40.530
high-quality latitude
and longitude.

00:34:40.530 --> 00:34:43.139
We haven't surfaced the level
yet so we can't say you're on

00:34:43.139 --> 00:34:43.889
Level Two of Moscone.

00:34:43.889 --> 00:34:47.590
We're still working on that,
but it's coming.

00:34:47.590 --> 00:34:50.830
So in the short term, this is
what we plan to work on.

00:34:50.830 --> 00:34:54.120
It's this question of, can
we do more indoor venues?

00:34:54.120 --> 00:34:56.960
And we're going to keep growing
them, and people are

00:34:56.960 --> 00:34:59.990
uploading them to our servers
all the time.

00:34:59.990 --> 00:35:01.370
It's really awesome.

00:35:01.370 --> 00:35:03.890
We want to improve the quality
of the indoor location, and

00:35:03.890 --> 00:35:06.720
that's going to happen through a
lot of different mechanisms.

00:35:06.720 --> 00:35:09.600
One is technological, because
there are new technologies

00:35:09.600 --> 00:35:12.410
coming along the way, like
Bluetooth Low Energy, and even

00:35:12.410 --> 00:35:13.460
the humble Wi-Fi.

00:35:13.460 --> 00:35:16.090
Finally, they're going to start
adding something called

00:35:16.090 --> 00:35:18.920
802.11B, which gives you time of
flight, which gives you an

00:35:18.920 --> 00:35:20.280
estimate of the distance.

00:35:20.280 --> 00:35:23.230
So those new technologies that
come online, we're going to

00:35:23.230 --> 00:35:27.150
mix them straight into that
sensor fusion process to give

00:35:27.150 --> 00:35:30.830
you even higher-quality
location.

00:35:30.830 --> 00:35:33.040
Not only that, but we can do
amazing things like you can

00:35:33.040 --> 00:35:34.110
match against the map.

00:35:34.110 --> 00:35:36.600
You can use the map to constrain
where people are to

00:35:36.600 --> 00:35:38.830
get even higher accuracy.

00:35:38.830 --> 00:35:41.140
And the thing that we're really
interested in is more

00:35:41.140 --> 00:35:43.330
improvements for API
developments.

00:35:43.330 --> 00:35:47.110
Now when it comes to the longer
term, this is what I'm

00:35:47.110 --> 00:35:48.290
really excited about.

00:35:48.290 --> 00:35:50.730
So clearly, we talked about
Google Maps and navigation and

00:35:50.730 --> 00:35:51.800
those types of capabilities.

00:35:51.800 --> 00:35:54.540
They're kind of awesome, but
there's something more.

00:35:54.540 --> 00:35:58.100
Now, if you remember back to
what Larry said this morning

00:35:58.100 --> 00:36:01.450
at the keynote, he mentioned
that it's really important

00:36:01.450 --> 00:36:03.570
that we make smarter
applications.

00:36:03.570 --> 00:36:09.080
And Amit talked about the
"Star Trek" computer.

00:36:09.080 --> 00:36:10.690
So I have a question for you.

00:36:10.690 --> 00:36:14.420
Would the "Star Trek" computer
be useful if it didn't have

00:36:14.420 --> 00:36:17.270
floor plans of the Starship
Enterprise?

00:36:17.270 --> 00:36:18.980
That's the question I want
you to think about.

00:36:18.980 --> 00:36:21.350
If you are building contractual
apps that are

00:36:21.350 --> 00:36:25.170
meant to be smarter, that look
out for information for the

00:36:25.170 --> 00:36:28.140
user like Google Now for those
of you who have used Google

00:36:28.140 --> 00:36:31.950
Now, how can you make those
applications work if you're

00:36:31.950 --> 00:36:34.790
not really aware of where
people spend so

00:36:34.790 --> 00:36:36.470
much of their time?

00:36:36.470 --> 00:36:38.960
And I wanted to kind of show
you guys through the

00:36:38.960 --> 00:36:41.090
applications we've kind
of been toying with.

00:36:41.090 --> 00:36:42.880
This is not a launched
application.

00:36:42.880 --> 00:36:44.170
It's just a demo app.

00:36:44.170 --> 00:36:45.650
But what we did was
just for fun.

00:36:45.650 --> 00:36:47.590
We built what we call
Friends in a Mall.

00:36:47.590 --> 00:36:51.200
So we surveyed a big mall, and
then what we did is we just

00:36:51.200 --> 00:36:53.700
had it so it would report
where people were.

00:36:53.700 --> 00:36:57.760
And when we went out there
testing this, the engineers

00:36:57.760 --> 00:36:58.240
were giggling.

00:36:58.240 --> 00:37:00.670
We could imagine a lot of the
different applications people

00:37:00.670 --> 00:37:01.830
could build.

00:37:01.830 --> 00:37:04.230
Imagine you and your spouse
going to the shopping mall,

00:37:04.230 --> 00:37:07.070
and he or she wants to buy
something, and you want to buy

00:37:07.070 --> 00:37:09.300
something else, then
you can split up.

00:37:09.300 --> 00:37:12.310
Imagine the opportunities here
for serendipitous encounters

00:37:12.310 --> 00:37:14.220
when friends that you trust
that you've shared your

00:37:14.220 --> 00:37:17.380
location with can appear on
the map, and you can just

00:37:17.380 --> 00:37:20.760
catch up with them because you
found them by coincidence.

00:37:20.760 --> 00:37:24.550
So this is one thing that
really made us feel that

00:37:24.550 --> 00:37:28.180
indoor is kind of key to these
kind of contextual apps.

00:37:28.180 --> 00:37:31.170
And the fast refresh rate, it
was just a really, really

00:37:31.170 --> 00:37:32.840
compelling experience.

00:37:32.840 --> 00:37:35.230
And the second thing was I want
to show you what we call

00:37:35.230 --> 00:37:36.440
the invisible search term.

00:37:36.440 --> 00:37:38.630
So let's say we're now
at Home Depot.

00:37:38.630 --> 00:37:41.210
At Home Depot, imagine that
you're in the painting

00:37:41.210 --> 00:37:44.990
department, and you search for
"painting." So do you expect

00:37:44.990 --> 00:37:48.840
the Mona Lisa, or do you expect
to cover your wall with

00:37:48.840 --> 00:37:50.730
icky yellow stuff?

00:37:50.730 --> 00:37:53.300
If I'm in Home Depot, I know I
should be getting the second

00:37:53.300 --> 00:37:54.030
search result.

00:37:54.030 --> 00:37:57.480
But let's say you're in the de
Young Museum, which is also a

00:37:57.480 --> 00:38:00.860
venue that we have indoor floor
plans for, and you do

00:38:00.860 --> 00:38:03.720
the same search, exactly
the same term.

00:38:03.720 --> 00:38:06.730
Don't you get exactly the
opposite search results?

00:38:06.730 --> 00:38:09.360
So this is what we mean by using
indoor for contextual

00:38:09.360 --> 00:38:11.610
applications, and this is what
I'm really excited to talk to

00:38:11.610 --> 00:38:13.070
you about today.

00:38:13.070 --> 00:38:16.580
And this is why task-oriented
applications, the conventional

00:38:16.580 --> 00:38:19.312
question answering, yes, indoors
is useful for that.

00:38:19.312 --> 00:38:21.600
But I want to see what you guys
as developers come up

00:38:21.600 --> 00:38:23.170
with on this front.

00:38:23.170 --> 00:38:27.390
So the key takeaways, before we
go on, is you know Google's

00:38:27.390 --> 00:38:29.200
mission as well as we do--
organize the world's

00:38:29.200 --> 00:38:30.610
information and make
it universally

00:38:30.610 --> 00:38:31.670
accessible and useful.

00:38:31.670 --> 00:38:34.550
But how can you do that if you
don't know about the place

00:38:34.550 --> 00:38:36.490
where people spend so
much of their time?

00:38:36.490 --> 00:38:37.590
It's a very active field.

00:38:37.590 --> 00:38:39.270
We've launched three countries
in the last three months.

00:38:39.270 --> 00:38:42.970
There's so much else going on,
and we're even making more

00:38:42.970 --> 00:38:45.070
APIs available to developers.

00:38:45.070 --> 00:38:47.750
And what I'm really excited to
talk to you about, what I

00:38:47.750 --> 00:38:50.060
really think is the potential of
indoor, is these contextual

00:38:50.060 --> 00:38:52.840
apps, and that's the question
I want to leave you with.

00:38:52.840 --> 00:38:53.880
What are you going to do?

00:38:53.880 --> 00:38:56.600
How can you use indoor
information to make the apps

00:38:56.600 --> 00:38:59.610
that you guys deliver and make
available to your users even

00:38:59.610 --> 00:39:00.650
more awesome?

00:39:00.650 --> 00:39:02.390
So thank you very much.

00:39:02.390 --> 00:39:03.240
A few quick pointers.

